<LP>
   S&amp;P LOWERED its ratings on debt issued by Chrysler and
Ford, and affirmed ratings for GM. The agency, which cited
growing competition and soft auto demand, downgraded Ford's
senior debt to double-A-minus and Chrysler's to
triple-B-minus, one notch above speculative grade.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A serious credit crunch extends well beyond the real
estate industry and appears to be worsening, Commerce
Secretary Mosbacher said.
   ---
   Reebok said its biggest shareholder, Pentland Group of
London, plans to sell its 31.5% stake. The sneaker company
promptly adopted a "poison pill" takeover defense.
   ---
   Gold prices tumbled on Saudi sales of the metal and the
prospect of sales by the Soviets to raise cash. Central banks
swooped into the market with big buy orders to halt the
decline.
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices eased amid growing concern about corporate
earnings, while bonds gained. The Dow Jones industrials fell
1.48 to 2928.22.
   ---
   The Soviet Union's economic uncertainty is hindering the
country's efforts to secure new Western loans as wary
British, Swiss and German bankers demand steeply higher
rates.
   ---
   CBS and ABC adopted NBC's plan to reduce the audience size
that the network guarantees advertisers.
   ---
   The Big Board's acceleration of plans for off-hours stock
trading was triggered by fears about competing efforts by
over-the-counter dealers and by the Big Board's own members.
   ---
   Producer prices rose 0.3% in May, reversing three months
of decline. The report suggests that inflation is likely to
continue at a moderate pace.
   ---
   Orix won the rights to buy 74 Airbus planes that Braniff
had ordered, and plans to becomes Japan's first
aircraft-leasing concern.
   ---
   Southland sweetened its exchange offer to bondholders by
about $200 million. The plan would slash the Thompson
family's equity stake.
   ---
   The thrift bailout will require an additional $30 billion
to $50 billion in funding next year, Brady projected,
generating criticism from Democrats.
                                                                                                       

   The Resolution Trust Corp. can override state laws to
permit the sale of failed S&amp;Ls to banks, a judge ruled.
   ---
   The Senate approved a resolution to cap fiscal 1991
discretionary spending at this year's level.
   ---
   Philips warned that second-quarter profit will fall
"appreciably" and that full-year results will be "very low."
The Dutch electronics giant is in the midst of a management
shake-up.
   ---
   U.S. auto makers intend to boost output in the third
quarter, despite disappointing sales. The plans reflect lean
inventories and labor concerns.
   ---
   Honeywell petitioned the government to halt imports of
Minolta automatic-focusing cameras, saying they violate the
U.S. company's patents.
   ---
   A $55 billion farm bill cleared a House panel. It includes
a new policy on soil and water conservation.
   ---
